I would have added a select() for the pipes a while ago but it's not clear to me how to implement it in a way that is both robust and efficient. Maybe if I looked into it in more detail a reasonable solution would become obvious, but I'm also not convinced that using some kind of select() would result in simpler client code than framing approaches like the type_safe_union or any other user defined framing method.

For example, wouldn't it have been easier to so something like this?

```
dlib::pipe<std::pair<int,yourdata>> p(10);
...
std::pair<int,yourdata> data;
while(p.dequeue(data))
{
    // use data.first to recognize which radio the stuff in data.second came from.
} 
```
   
It's not clear to me that a select() based system would result in simpler client code.  How would select() tell you which pipe has data?  Something like `int id = select(p1,p2,p3,p4,p5,p6);` where the id tells you which parameter is ready?

