@Tarrasch Hi yes, still using luigi. 

The use case for this was that certain third parties provide logs to us hourly. However, if their systems have issues (which seems to happen with some frequency) then instead of going back to populate missed logs (e.g. the log file for 3am) they'll just roll the data that would have been in that file into the next one they send (e.g. the one for 4am will contain the data for 3am and 4am). This meant that we were having luigi tasks waiting indefinitely for files that would never appear (e.g. for 3am in this scenario).

This patch means that we can set a parameter to say "keep trying for 2 days then just die". We monitor the output of our important workflows but for tasks like the above, since it's documented behaviour with our third party, there's not much else we can do but to just ignore these failures. Since we don't want processes piling up on our scheduler indefinitely, killing them after a hard timeout is the way to go.

