@notoriousno - The main thing is that thanks to its synchronous session-store API and hard-coded ID generation, it effectively thinks that your sessions are all going to be local state in a single process.  I'm not even sure if it's *possible* to work around that.

The reason we need session functionality is #126; you can't securely handle *any* input from a browser unless you have a mechanism for identifying actors and associating tokens with their intent, which means server-side state, which means session IDs.  You can see my prototype branch for this at https://github.com/glyph/klein/tree/form-hacks if you want to opine :).  Hopefully I'll do a proper PR soon, once I'm sure a whole application hangs together nicely.

I haven't had a chance to look at that particular link, I'm not really a fan of "middleware" as a concept.  The problem is that it takes a bunch of very specific, almost always security-sensitive attributes that an application needs, and attempts to factor them out into  a separate layer, so you can run the same code with or without sessions, or with or without authentication.  Generally speaking I don't think code which requires parameters should have the option to run *without* those parameters, so if you need "a logged in user" or "a session ID", you should very tightly bind to a system that is going to provide those to you.

