Lists that are not recursive are supported in our protobuf schema (though each element of the list must be the same type, one of `string`, `number` or `boolean`), so the following is permissible:

    {... "Fields": {"foo": ["bar", "baz"]}}

but not:

    {... "Fields": {"foo": ["bar", 1]}}

The new implementation will simply emit:

    {... "Fields": {"foo": "[\"bar\", \"baz\"]"}}

or

    {... "Fields": {"foo": "[\"bar\", 1]"}}

both of which are permissible, but in theory the former entry should be left as-is and the latter should either be considered an error or serialized to a JSON string (which is what the new implementation does).

As it happens, it may be easier simply to serialize all lists to avoid having to differentiate the two cases above, but I thought I would mention that the former is natively supported. If you choose to keep the current implementation, bear in mind that array fields serialized as JSON strings will incur a JSON decode downstream if they are processed, and also be more difficult to search for in elasticsearch.

